Moats and Open Source
---------------------

There was a fair bit of buzz last leak over an alleged internal Google memo=
 that was leaked to SemiAnalysis entitled We Have No Moat, And Neither Does=
 OpenAI ( https://www.semianalysis.com/p/google-we-have-no-moat-and-neither=
 ).

We=E2=80=99ve done a lot of looking over our shoulders at OpenAI. Who will =
cross the next milestone? What will the next move be? But the uncomfortable=
 truth is, we aren=E2=80=99t positioned to win this arms race and neither i=
s OpenAI. While we=E2=80=99ve been squabbling, a third faction has been qui=
etly eating our lunch. I=E2=80=99m talking, of course, about open source. P=
lainly put, they are lapping us. Things we consider =E2=80=9Cmajor open pro=
blems=E2=80=9D are solved and in people=E2=80=99s hands today. Just to name=
 a few:

* *LLMs on a Phone:* People are running foundation models on a Pixel 6 ( ht=
tps://twitter.com/thiteanish/status/1635678053853536256 ) at 5 tokens/sec.
* *Scalable Personal AI:* You can finetune a personalized AI on your laptop=
 in an evening. ( https://github.com/tloen/alpaca-lora ).
* *Responsible Release:* This one isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Csolved=E2=80=9D so=
 much as =E2=80=9Cobviated=E2=80=9D. There are entire websites full of art =
models with no restrictions whatsoever ( https://civitai.com/ ) , and text =
is not far behind. ( https://medium.com/geekculture/list-of-open-sourced-fi=
ne-tuned-large-language-models-llm-8d95a2e0dc76 )
* *Multimodality:* The current multimodal ScienceQA SOTA was trained in an =
hour ( https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.16199.pdf ).

While our models still hold a slight edge in terms of quality, the gap is c=
losing astonishingly quickly ( https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.16199.pdf ). Open=
-source models are faster, more customizable, more private, and pound-for-p=
ound more capable. They are doing things with $100 and 13B params ( https:/=
/lmsys.org/blog/2023-03-30-vicuna/ ) that we struggle with at $10M and 540B=
. And they are doing so in weeks, not months.

The rest of the memo lays out the case; I thought the most compelling secti=
on was the part arguing that speed of iteration and stacking improvements w=
ere essential to getting better, and that open source had an advantage over=
 large training runs in these two areas.

Still, while I=E2=80=99m obviously extremely interested in and excited abou=
t open source models, the author may have overstated his case a bit. Shital=
 Shah ( https://twitter.com/sytelus/status/1654357815060992003 ) has a long=
 tweet arguing that most open source benchmarking isn=E2=80=99t reliable (w=
hich is to say that their performance isn=E2=80=99t nearly as good as, say,=
 GPT-3, much less GPT-4), and Nathan Labenz ( https://twitter.com/labenz/st=
atus/1654853321876815872 ) has a thread arguing that, amongst other things,=
 the OpenAI=E2=80=99s aggressive movement down the pricing curve will forec=
lose any real economic opportunity for open source alternatives, ultimately=
 starving them of resources (including user data). For my part I will note =
that one of the big takeaways I had from ChatGPT is just how important and =
effective reinforcement learning with human feedback is to the user experie=
nce; that=E2=80=99s also a fairly expensive proposition that open source al=
ternatives may not be able to match.

The biggest pushback I have to the memo, though, is that any determination =
of a moat is inextricably tied to the business model a particular bit of te=
chnology is attached to, which is to say that any sort of blanket statement=
 misses important nuance. Take Google itself: the general way in which its =
search engine works is understood, but small distinctions in quality still =
matter; it also matters that Google is the default almost everywhere, that =
it gets much more user data, has such a huge advertising base, etc. It may =
be the case that in a few years we look at ChatGPT in a similar way ( https=
://stratechery.com/2023/the-accidental-consumer-tech-company-chatgpt-meta-a=
